'''''Trochus bellardii''''' is a [[species]] of [[sea snail]] with a [[top]]-shaped shell, a marine [[gastropod]] [[mollusk]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Trochidae]], the top snails.<ref name="WoRMS">{{WRMS species|216329|''Trochus bellardii'' Issel, 1869||1 May 2010}}</ref>

==Description==
The minute, thin shell has a height of only 2 mm. Its shape is orbicular-depressed, oblique, narrowly umbilicate, transversely minutely costulate. It has a pale rose-color, tessellated with purple. The [[Spire (mollusc)|spire]] isobtuse. The 4<U+00BD> [[Whorl (mollusc)|whorl]]s are rapidly widening, slightly convex, and planulate at the [[Suture (anatomy)|sutur]]es. They are separated by impressed sutures. The [[body whorl]] is large and rounded on the base. The [[Aperture (mollusc)|aperture]] is dilated, ovate-trigonal. The [[Peristome (gastropod)|peristome]] is simple and acute. <ref> [http://ia700307.us.archive.org/4/items/manualofconcholo111tryo/manualofconcholo111tryo.pdf Tryon (1889), Manual of Conchology XI, Academy of Natural Sciences, Philadelphia] </ref>

==Distribution==
This species occurs in the Red Sea off [[Suez]].

